description.en: Simple ontology for Cloud Computing Services. This ontology allows to define model of prices used in large cloud computing providers such as Google, Amazon, Azure, etc., including options for regions, type of instances, prices specification, etc.

comment.en: Storage that is not detachable from VM
Gigabyte (GB): There are 1024MB in one gigabyte.

GCEU (Google Compute Engine Unit), or GQ for short, is a unit of CPU capacity that we use to describe the compute power of our instance types. We chose 2.75 GQ's to represent the minimum power of one logical core (a hardware hyper-thread) on our Sandy Bridge platform.
Often describe 1 GB per Month usage.
Terabyte is more precisely defined as 1,024 gigabytes (GB)
Often describe the throughput usage measured at MB/s within an hour.

Azure Ultra SSD storage is in preview in East US 2 and is billed on vcpu/hour provisioned as reservation charge. This reservation charge is only imposed if you enable Ultra SSD capability on the VM without connecting an Ultra SSD disk.
Azure Managed Disks provide different input/output operations per sec (IOPs)
Often describe 1 GB per Hour usage.
Azure Ultra SSD Managed Disks come in different sizes that provide a configurable range of input/output operations per sec (IOPS), and are billed on an hourly rate.
Defines custome units.
Infrastructure as a Service
This class can be used to model network services prices, including internet egress traffic, load balancing forwarding rules.

Can be used to define a common price spec for multiple cloud service individuals,
i.e. the storage transaction spec has a different price in a different region,
but there is a common transaction price spec for a group of cloud storage offers.
Software as a Service
Platform as a Service, i.e. Google App Engine, Heroku.
